haining, that is, defeating an opponent by casting a series of elementals at the enemy as each one dies, is a major fighting technique, and one of the only ways mages have for coping with adds, either solo, or in groups.<br>
<br>
Chaining pets is generally more mana efficient, although more time consuming, than sustaining a single elemental during a fight.  It is the <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">only</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> way I can solo at 63rd level in the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Planes of Power</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Dark blue trash in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Plane of Nightmare</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> takes anywhere from 4 to 7 pets to kill.  Most of them do not live long enough to make buffing a worthwhile use of mana, so they fight in their raw, unbuffed state, with no weapons and no haste.  Yet, they withstand the enemy and deal enough damage to reduce the foe's health by 15-25% health per pet.  Unbuffed.<br>
<br>
Mages have a class AA, called <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Improved Reclaim Energy</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which allows the mage to reclaim an injured pet for its full mana cost.  Groups of mages are thus able to sustain multiple pets indefinitely with no net mana cost, and beat down a surprising variety of enemies.  Against hard hitting <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Tier 2+</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mobs, these pets again do not as individuals survive long enough to be worth buffing, but in the end they drag the foe to their doom, as surely as the tides wear a cliff away.  While time consuming, it works, and depends on the ability of pets to fight immediately upon being summoned.<br>
<br>
I have not played any class beyond 35th level except magicians, and I do not pretend more than a cursory knowledge of the abilities, tactics, or issues of other classes.  For example, when <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Natan</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> suggested an alternate spell list for a caster fire pet, I freely admitted that I did not know the spells in question, and could not judge their worth or appropriateness.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, you claim that my understanding of the foundations of the mage class are incorrect.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Gwideon The Gnome:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  As much as I respect Rombus's opinion, I think concussion should be left to the Wizard. If Mages received concussion, even as a pet ability, I would vehemently appose it.  Magicians already have enough agro-less damage in their pets and damage shields.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->As things stand, I agree.  However, there was some discussion by Sony of changing the aggro rules for magical damage.  In that case, mages <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">might</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> well need something like concussion to remain competitive.  There is also some concern expressed by high-end mages that in end-game raids, mages are more aggro bound than other casters <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">and</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> pets are nigh useless in those fights.  <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">If</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> that is the case, <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">then</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> some form of aggro reduction for mages is a possible solution and worth discussing.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Knobby:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  YAY Balanz for saving me from Carpal Tunnels<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Almost 30 years programming, and still no sign of it.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Praise Karana!</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Cyricus:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I would like to see who wants them to? I would say 90% of all Mages only want a pet on par with the other 3 pets<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Well, if you read the thread in question, the majority reaction of mages to the fire pet possibly casting <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Ice Comet</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> was basically: <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Way cool!&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  I think this is attributeable to the joy of the possibility that the fire pet might go from suckage to ruleage, and was not well thought out.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Ice Comet</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">is</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> one of the most visually pleasing spells, and I am sure that has something to do with it.  Indeed, only the visuals tempt me.<br>
<br>
I think that when the objections are pointed out, that indeed, 90% of all mages would be simply delighted if the pet did not suck.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Natan:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I think the truth behind all the euphorism is, that a lot of Mages realyl want to be like Wizards, more or less.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I for one could never stand being or playing a wizard.  This is a matter of playing style, mind you, and not a judgment on the worth of the wizard class.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Karana</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> granted us elementals so they could pound the snot out of the enemy.  Love the pet, love the elemental.  I do not want to resemble wizards; I specifically do not want to kite.  Running from the enemy should be a matter of last resort, not a major tactic.<br>
