<br>
Pet chaining is not the only way mages fight and for the most part is not the way they have fought throughout the majority of the history of the game.  It isn't even until level 44 or so that the tactic becomes viable, and while it may still be viable for a level 63 mage to get xp in this manner, level 65 mages are BUFFING up their pets and soloing in plane of storms against caster mobs.  From what I have read this is possible from level 61 on so if you truly believe that the the only way I can solo at 63rd level in the Planes of Power is to chain pets then you are mistaken.<br>
<br>
Where you and I differ is really on what we think the role the fire pet should play.  You believe it should be sustainable dps to which I say that mages already have a pet (the water pet) that can perform that role adequately.  Furthermore, if the fire pet offered better sustainable dps than the water pet then that would solve nothing.  The water pet would simply go to the back of the spell book where the fire pet currently is.  Mages would still have one useless pet.  In order for this pet to have a role it would need to provide something else.  I believe that role should be one of the following: a) burst dps b) utility c) situational use.  <br>
<br>
Because I don't view the pet as a source of sustainable dps, I don't have a problem with it being summoned oom.  Now you may believe that the role of a mage pet is always that sustainable dps.  But that belief is not necessarily shared by all mages.  From your post, I get the impression you think I am a wizard.  My main is a level 65 mage on the Mithaniel Marr server with over 270 days played.  <br>
<br>
When I summon an air pet it is for the utility of its stun.  When I summon an earth pet, it is for the utility of its root.  We have four different pets and just because one of them is an exceptional source of sustainable dps is no reason to believe all four should be.<br>
<br>
Regarding, your statement<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;On the other hand, you claim that my understanding of the foundations of the mage class are incorrect.<br>
<br>
I think that overstates my point a bit.  I do believe that your place too much emphasis on chaining pets and not enough emphasis your pets other attributes, a belief your latest post has reinforced.<br>
